{{Use Australian English|date=September 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}} {{Infobox organization |name = Australian Libraries Copyright Committee |named_after = |image = |caption = |logo = |logo_caption = |motto = |predecessor = |merged = |successor = |formation = 1994 |founder = Tom Cochrane |founding_location = |extinction = |merger = |type = |status = |purpose = |headquarters = [[National Library of Australia]] |location = [[Canberra]] |region = |services = |products = |methods = |fields = |membership = |membership_year = |language = |owner = |sec_gen = |leader_title = Chair |leader_name = Margaret Allen |board_of_directors = |key_people = |main_organ = |parent_organization = |subsidiaries = |secessions = |affiliations = [[Australian Digital Alliance]] |website = [http://libcopyright.org.au/ www.libcopyright.org.au]}}
The '''Australian Libraries Copyright Committee''' (ALCC) is an Australian organisation dealing with [[Copyright law of Australia|copyright law]]. It has a particular focus with relevance for the [[GLAM (industry sector)|GLAM]] sector in Australia.<ref>{{Citation | title=Flexible dealing and cultural institutions : statement of principles regarding the use of section 200AB of the Copyright Act (1968): an industry standard and user guide for the cultural sector | publication-date=2010 | publisher=Copyright in Cultural Institutions | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/38424386 | accessdate=27 September 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Dawes, Matt | title=Copyright and Libraries: The ALCC | journal=Incite | publication-date=July 2010 | volume=31 | issue=7 | pages=14 | issn=0158-0876 }}</ref> It is related to the [[Australian Digital Alliance]].<ref>{{Citation | title=Copyright and the digital economy submission by the Australian Digital Alliance and Australian Libraries Copyright Committee to the Australian Law Reform Commission | publication-date=2012 | publisher=Australian Libraries Copyright Commission | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/177307101 | accessdate=27 September 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Australian Digital AllianceAustralian Libraries' Copyright Committee | title=High Court acknowledges importance of fair copyright and broader public interest | publication-date=7 October 2005 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/193017065 | accessdate=27 September 2018 }}</ref>
Formed in 1994 to attend to copyright issues affecting the library, archive and information sectors, the ALCC became an incorporated body in 2015.<ref> [https://libcopyright.org.au/who-we-are Who we are] Australian Libraries Copyright Committee</ref> The ALCC is focused upon law reform in the Australian legal system.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Simes, Laura | title=AL C - Australian Libraries Copyright Committee | journal=Incite | publication-date=December 2007 | volume=28 | issue=12 | pages=31, 33 | issn=0158-0876 }}</ref> It regularly provides updated information and interpretation about legislation.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Smith, Nick, 1971- | author2=Australian Council of Libraries and Information Services | author3=Australian Libraries Copyright Committee | title=Copyright bulletin | publication-date=1994 | publisher=Australian Council of Libraries and Information Services | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7886202 | accessdate=27 September 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=Simes, Laura | author2=Simes, Laura | author3=National Library of Australia (issuing body.) | author4=Australian Digital Alliance (issuing body.) | author5=Australian Libraries Copyright Committee (issuing body.) | author6=Simes, Laura | title=A user's guide to the flexible dealing provision for libraries, educational institutions and cultural institutions : section 200AB of the copyright act 1968 (Cth) | publication-date=2008 | publisher=Australian Libraries Copyright Committee and the Australian Digital Alliance with the assistance of the National Library of Australia | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/31020696 | accessdate=27 September 2018 }}</ref>
Legislation relative to copyright issues with Australia being signatory to international treaties, has seen the committee attend to low level publicised legislation such as the Disability and Other Measures Act.<ref>[https://www.legislation.gov.au/details/c2017a00049 Copyright Amendment (Disability Access and Other Measures) Act 2017] Federal Register of Legislation</ref>
The ALCC is based at the [[National Library of Australia]] in [[Canberra]].<ref>[http://libcopyright.org.au/who-we-are Contact us] Australian Libraries Copyright Committee</ref>
