'''Carol Christine Smart'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/580999/new-years-honours-2017-full-list.pdf|format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]]|date=30 December 2016|accessdate=30 December 2016|work=[[Gov.uk]]|publisher=[[Government Digital Service]]|title=New Year's Honours list 2017|page=19}}</ref> {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}} (born 20 December 1948<ref name=Congress>{{cite web |title= Smart, Carol |url= http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n83155723.html |publisher= Library of Congress |accessdate= 18 July 2014 |quote= CIP t.p. (Carol Smart) data sheet (b. 12-20-48)}}</ref>) is a feminist sociologist and academic at the [[University of Manchester]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/why-dumping-a-friend-is-hard-1941432.html |title=  Why dumping a friend is hard |last=Lakhani |first=Nina |date= 10 April 2010|work=The Independent |accessdate=12 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialsciences.manchester.ac.uk/morgancentre/people/smart/|title=Carol Smart  |publisher=Morgan Centre for the Study of Relationships and Personal Life|accessdate=12 April 2010}}</ref> She has also conducted research about divorce and children of divorced couples.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/oct/17/gender.children|title=Why a child is not a house|last=Phillips|first=Angela |date=17 October 2003 |work= The Guardian|quote=New research from a longitudinal study by Carol Smart of the Care, Values and the Future of Welfare (Cava) research programme at the University of Leeds asked children what it actually feels like to be shared.|accessdate=12 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/03/26/1079939846142.html|title=New parental etiquette   |last=Horin |first=Adele |authorlink = Adele Horin |date=27 March 2004|work=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=12 April 2010}}</ref>

Smart is an important figure within the feminist criminology world. Her book titled ''Women, Crime and Criminology'',<ref>{{cite book | last = Smart | first = Carol | title = Women, crime, and criminology: a feminist critique | publisher = Routledge & K. Paul | location = London Boston | year = 1977 | isbn = 9780710088338 }}</ref> written in 1976, remains a key feminist critique of criminology. Smart was also the co-director of the [[Arthur Lewis Building|Morgan Centre for the Study of Relationships and Personal Life]] at Manchester.

== Career ==
Smart began her academic career by studying sociology at [[Portsmouth Polytechnic]], which is now [[Portsmouth University]]. After completing her BA, she moved on to complete her masters in criminology from the [[University of Sheffield]]. She also completed her PhD in Socio-Legal studies also from Sheffield in 1983.

Smart began her teaching career at the then, Trent Polytechnic, (as a lecturer and senior lecturer). After that, she became a professor at the [[University of Leeds]]. In 2005, she moved to the Morgan Centre for the Study of Relationships and Personal Life in the [[Arthur Lewis Building]] of the University of Manchester, where she was co-director. She retired in 2014<ref name="offhp">{{Cite web |url=http://www.manchester.ac.uk/research/Carol.smart/ |title=Prof Carol Smart - personal details}}</ref>.

Smart has published works in the areas of criminology, family law and social policy. Her main interests over the last few years have been family life and intimacy and how people conduct their personal lives. Smart has done much research on divorce and separation and how this affects children, the couple and other kin, and on gay and lesbian civil partnerships and their commitment ceremonies. More recently she has been working on 'Relative Strangers',<ref>http://www.socialsciences.manchester.ac.uk/morgancentre/research/relative-strangers/index.html</ref> a project which explores the experiences of families with donor-conceived children.

She was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the [[2017 New Year Honours]] for services to the social sciences.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61803|supp=y|page=N10|date=31 December 2016}}</ref>

