{{Politics of Denmark}}
A '''constitutional and electoral age referendum''' was held in [[Denmark]] on 28 May 1953.<ref name=DN>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] & Stöver, P (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p524 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref> Both proposals were approved by voters, leading to both a new [[Danish constitution|constitution]] taking effect on 5 June, and the [[electoral age]] being lowered from 25 to 23 years, also starting on 5 June.<ref name="grundloven">[http://www.folketinget.dk/pdf/constitution.pdf http://www.folketinget.dk/pdf/constitution.pdf] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227110116/http://www.folketinget.dk/pdf/constitution.pdf |date=February 27, 2008 }}</ref><ref name="retsinfo">[http://www.retsinfo.dk/_GETDOCI_/ACCN/A19530016930-REGL http://www.retsinfo.dk/_GETDOCI_/ACCN/A19530016930-REGL] {{da icon}}</ref><ref name="duf">http://www.duf.dk/servlet/SaveImage?URL=http://web/data.nsf/webDocuments/0238362B6A7EBF55C1256D4E003A34C4/$file/16aar-valgret-hvadskaldertil.doc {{da icon}}</ref> Voter turnout was 59.1% for the constitution question and 57.1% for the voting age question.<ref>Nohlen & Stöver, 532-533</ref>
==Constitution== According to the previous constitution of 1915, with changes from 1920, in order for a new constitution to pass, it must first be passed in one [[Rigsdag]], which must then be disbanded, a new parliamentary [[election]] called, and the new parliament must then also pass the constitution, in unchanged form; and finally, a majority of voters in a referendum, with a requirement of at least 45% turnout, must also pass the proposed constitution.<ref name="old constitution">[http://thomasthorsen.dk/dk-co-1920.html http://thomasthorsen.dk/dk-co-1920.html] {{da icon}}</ref> When the referendum took place on May 28, 1953, it concluded the last of these three steps, and the constitution could take effect on June 5.
===Changes from the previous constitution=== The [[Ministry of Education of Denmark]] lists the changes from the previous constitution as follows:<ref name="uvm">[http://sekr.uvm.dk/historie/tekster_tidssoejle/tid_hist/dan_16_grundlov_53.html http://sekr.uvm.dk/historie/tekster_tidssoejle/tid_hist/dan_16_grundlov_53.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719132841/http://sekr.uvm.dk/historie/tekster_tidssoejle/tid_hist/dan_16_grundlov_53.html |date=2011-07-19 }} {{da icon}}</ref> * The [[Danish Act of Succession|Act of Succession]] was changed so that females could also inherit the [[Danish throne]], though still preferring even younger brothers. As the reigning King [[Frederick IX of Denmark|Frederick IX]] had three daughters and no sons, this meant that [[Margrethe II of Denmark|Princess Margrethe]] became the [[Heir Presumptive]] instead of her uncle [[Knud, Hereditary Prince of Denmark|Prince Knud]]. As Frederick IX's wife [[Ingrid of Sweden|Queen Ingrid]] was not expected to (and in fact did not) have any more children, this effectively ensured that Princess Margrethe would become [[Queen of Denmark]], which she did. * [[Parliamentarism]], in the sense that no government may have a majority of members of parliament against it, is made explicit in the constitution. (This principle had de facto existed since 1901, but the 1953 constitution made it law). * The [[Landsting (Denmark)|Landsting]] was abolished, and the [[Folketing]] expanded to 179 members. * Voting by [[convict]]s and the poor is no longer outlawed in the constitution, but subject to normal laws. * The electoral age was removed, to be decided by referendums. * [[Greenland]] was made a coequal part of Denmark, and would elect two members of parliament. * Referendums can be held over most kinds of laws, provided that one third of parliament demand it (this has only happened [[Danish land laws referendum, 1963|once]]). * Citizens' [[civil right]]s are increased. * The office of Folketing's [[ombudsman]] is established. * [[Sovereignty]] can be forfeited to what the constitution calls ''mellemfolkelige myndigheder'', which can include [[Supranational union]]s such as the current [[European Union]]. For this to take place, it must either happen with 5/6 of members of parliament voting in favour, or by holding a referendum.
==Voting age== One of the proposed changes in the new constitution was that the electoral age would now be decided by laws that required a binding referendum. Prior to the 1953 referendum, the electoral age was 25 years. The electoral age portion of the referendum asked whether the new electoral age should be 23 or 21 years, with 30.0% voting for 23 years and 25.0% for 21 years, thus passing the former of the two.<ref name="duf"/>
